               <p>1738. 
               
                  <persName id="t18300916-274-defend2260" type="defendantName">
                     HENRY 
                     LACEY
                  <interp inst="t18300916-274-defend2260" type="surname" value="LACEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-defend2260" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-defend2260" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
               
             was indicted for <rs id="t18300916-274-off1391" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-off1391" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-off1391" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18300916-274-cd1392" type="crimeDate">12th of July</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-274-off1391 t18300916-274-cd1392"></join>, 6 shillings, and the sum of 8d., in copper monies, the monies of 
                     
                        <persName id="t18300916-274-victim2262" type="victimName">
                           George 
                           Abledon
                        <interp inst="t18300916-274-victim2262" type="surname" value="Abledon"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300916-274-victim2262" type="given" value="George"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18300916-274-victim2262" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-274-off1391 t18300916-274-victim2262"></join>
                     </persName>
                     
                  , his master
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>GEORGE ABLEDON. I am a <rs id="t18300916-274-viclabel1393" type="occupation">baker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-274-victim2262 t18300916-274-viclabel1393"></join> - the prisoner was in my employ. On the 12th of August he took 6s. 8d. of Mrs. Bailey, of <placeName id="t18300916-274-crimeloc1394">Hackney</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-274-crimeloc1394" type="placeName" value="Hackney"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300916-274-crimeloc1394" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300916-274-off1391 t18300916-274-crimeloc1394"></join>; I sent him out with bread that day - she pays on Monday, and had two quartern loaves the week before; there was a little girl in my shop when he returned; I was just opposite - I asked him if he had paid; she said No - he went through into the bake-house: on the 8th of July, I sent him with some bread, which he did not deliver - he had delivered some to Mr. Bailey on the 7th; here are five quartern loaves down in the book on the 8th, but he did not deliver them - he asked for the five loaves, and I delivered them to him.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CHURCHILL. Q. Did you deliver the five loaves to him? A. Yes, on the Thursday; she never has bread on a Thursday, but he said she wanted eight; there are no names in this book, but he goes to four customers regularly in order, and we know by that who has them; he has entered the five on Thursday - mistakes have occurred with him before; he has come home short of bread sometimes - I thought at first it was a mistake, but afterwards I found he had sold them at 6d. a piece; I am obliged to attend in my shop, as my wife is ill - this young woman comes over an hour or two in the afternoon; the prisoner's book was on the shelf on the Friday where he always puts it - I had looked there before, and it was not there.</p>
               <p>COURT. Q. Did you ask on Friday for the money? A. No - I did not expect it till the following week.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-274-person2263">
                  SARAH 
                  BAILEY
               <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2263" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2263" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2263" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a customer of the prosecutor's; I have bread on the Monday, Wednesday, and Friday - I ordered none on the Thursday; I had paid the prisoner on the Monday; he did no charge for these five loaves - he did not come on the following Monday.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-274-person2264">
                  DAVID 
                  DEARMAN
               <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2264" type="surname" value="DEARMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2264" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2264" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . My mistress gave me the money to pay on the morning before, and I paid the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300916-274-person2265">
                  THOMAS 
                  VANN
               <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2265" type="surname" value="VANN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2265" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2265" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was sent for to the prosecutor's on the 17th of July; he charged the prisoner with robbing him of fifteen loaves; he said he had left ten at Bailey's, and put the money on the counter - two half-crowns, a shilling, a sixpence, and two pence; he said he knew nothing of the other five, but I said, "Try to recollect who you paid it to;" he said "The young woman was coming from the passage to the shop, and that was the very money I received from Bailey."</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. He was in his master's place? A. Yes.</p>
               <p>COURT to GEORGE ABLEDON. Q. Did you charge him with fifteen loaves? A. Yes; the ten Mrs. Bailey had the week before, and the five on the 8th - he said he had paid 
               <persName id="t18300916-274-person2266">
                  Martha 
                  Bright
               <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2266" type="surname" value="Bright"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2266" type="given" value="Martha"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-person2266" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             for the ten, but I did not ask about the five- I knew she had not had the money; I gave him in charge for having the five loaves, and not delivering them.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. He was still in your service? A. Yes; on the Saturday I sent for the officer - I had not told him before the officer arrived; I keep no books - it is a ready money business; the money is laid down - there is always some person within call to take it.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. My master states he is in the habit of paying attention to his business, but he is always in the Black Boy playing at cards - he is a pugifist; I was in the habit of taking five loaves on Monday, five on Wednesday, and five on Saturday to Mrs. Bailey, and if any other customer wanted them she had to go without till Saturday, as she knows.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18300916-274-verdict1395" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300916-274-verdict1395" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
